More and more people no longer read newspapers or watch TV programs to get news. They get news about the world through the Internet. It this a positive or negative development.
access information
shape public opinion
erode trust in credible journalism
attract online traffic

The digital age has fundamentally the way people access information, leading to a decline in the use of traditional news sources such as newspapers and television. This essay argues that relying primarily on the Internet for news is a negative development.
One major concern is the widespread presence of misinformation and fake news online. The low barrier to publishing content has enabled unverified sources to disseminate misleading or entirely false information. This can have serious consequences, as it may shape public opinion distort political discourse, and erode trust in credible journalism. For instance, conspirarcy theories often circulate widely on digital platforms, relying on half-truths and unsubstantiated claims. As a result, many individuals struggle to distinguish between reliable information and falsehoods, leading to a poorly informed public.
Another significant drawback is the negative impact on the quality of journalism. The rise of digital media has disrupted traditional revenue modals, leaving many newspapers and television networks financially strained. Consequently, some organizations are forced to reduce staff, limit investigative reporting, or prioritizing sensational content to attract online traffic. This shift can undermine journalistic standards and reduce the availability of in-depty, well-researched reporting, which is crucial for an informed society.
In conclusion, although the Internet provides quick and convenient access to news, an overreliance on it can be detrimental. To remain accurately informed, individuals should consider using a balanced combination of both traditional and digital news sources.
